ontexts,” examines language-related problems in selected institutional areas of communication (education, the law, religion, science, the Internet) which will often derive from socioeconomic, cultural and other non-linguistic asymmetries. Part IV, “The discourse of linguistic diversity and language change,” analyses linguistic diversity, language change and language reform as issues of public debates which are informed by different ideological positions, values and attitudes (e.g. with reference to sexism, racism, and political correctness).The volume also contains extensive reference sections and index material.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 0aLanguage planning. 0aLinguistic change. 0aLinguistic minorities. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aAngewandte Linguistik. 4aSoziolinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aApplied linguistics, lanuaga planning, language policy.1 aBieswanger, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlommaert, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonfiglio, Thomas Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrabant, Madeleine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalaresu, Emilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarli, Augusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanet, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aExtra, Guus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFill, Alwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallois, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4htt